title: For Sale:  WW2 GERMAN ARMY BINOCULARS KARL ZEISS BLC 1943 ISSUE WWII NAZI MILITARY SET
location: SF bay area, San Francisco, California
postcontent:
Nice original set of WWII German Army field binoculars. These are the nice, much larger 10 x 50 power armored-glass ( shatterproof) binoculars, not the small, much common 6x30 feldglas commonly used by ground units. Examples like these would have been utilized by officers, senior NCOs and Armored-unit and tank Commanders, as well as FlakArtillerie, Antiflugzeugbatterie or Forward-observer posts, NOT your everyday fernglas issued to line troops.

Completely original set, wartime-manufactured by KARL ZEISS in Jenna. Clearly wartime-coded " BLC " as marked, and they are also marked " + " for Cold-weather temperature use. That means the internal mechanisms, lenses and ocular pieces are treated with special internal lubricants to facilitate vision during inclement weather and prevent seizure of the mechanisms.

Clear optics, with no hazing or fungus. These WW 2 binoculars are also range- marked with the Artillery reticle inside the lenses. 
Adjustments function fine on both oculars. Some moderate wear to its original non-slip krinkle finish as expected from a wartime-used set, to reflect its honest age, not repainted. No rust or corrosion to lense cases or aluminium body.

        Original WWII military case is made of the correct Prestoff-type black leatherette for the period, wartime-dated 1943 and also coded with the " CNY " military manufacture code. The front-strap latch is stamped twice " fnh43 ".

The hinged leather-strap section is firm and not detached nor split. Original front leather strap pull still present. Its original neckstrap is also present, and in good condition with NO breaks, tears or splits.

Overall, a nice original set of WW2 German army set of binoculars, for the advanced collector. Ship USPS priority within 24 hrs. of receipt of payment, via USPS Priority with tracking.

WWII German Afrikakorps short combat boots. These were originally heavy-duty boots worn by Commonwealth troops in the North Africa campaigns since early 1941. Many examples like this were taken from captured Australian army stocks after the successful german advances into Tunisia and Libya in 1942. 

Over 18,000 British army and Commonwealth uniforms were captured after the siege and seizure of Tobruk by the AfrikaKorps. Among these, thousands of hardy Australian army combat boots, just as pictured here. You can see them in use by many DAK troops throughout North Africa in many pictorial and documented records and photographs. Some were even issued to Italian army units active in the area.




         They are heavy, wartime-manufactured of very sturdy natural leather. All leather is in excellent shape throughout the boots, with NO rips, tears, wear spots or any field repairs whatsoever. Original natural look is still remarkable. Approximate size is 8 1/2 ( the say 5 in UK size).  These are 1945 dated.

I had them with a WWII DAK static mannequin display for years, but I am very fortunate to have just received a set of salty original Afrikakorps boots from overseas ( yes, the insanely expensive and rare DAK short boots); thus, I have no further need for these anymore.
They are in unissued condition, with no wear other than being displayed in a mannequin. Unfortunately, the laces broke in several parts, but easy to replace.

        An original wartime-correct alternative to the fake Indian or Chinese-made SUPER CHEESY reproduction " Afrikakorps" boots that sell for over $270, or to paying over $1000 for an original pair of boots !              
GUARANTEED Shipping within 24 hours and receipt within FOUR DAYS.

title: For Sale:  MINT USMC M1951 COMBAT BOOTS M51 1951 DATE! PARAMARINE TYPE MARINE BOONDOCKERS
location: SF bay area, San Francisco, California
postcontent:
I've been looking for these for a while after I moved, and just found them in one of my boxes.  A set of MINT unissued US Marine Corps M1951 combat boots. They are very similar to the WWII "boondocker" boots used by the Corps in the Pacific during WW2. 

Contract dated January 1951, these were the high top rough side- out boots adopted during the Korean War......a much more sensible boot for cold weather wear than the WW2 vintage "boondockers". 
At some point I believe they became the standard issue Marine field boot but not sure when this happened. But I do recall seeing this boot, or one very similar, on the feet of "Old Corps" Marines as a little kid in the late 1960's.

The boots are stone-mint new, never even had a foot in them. They are both stamped " ENDICOTT JOHNSON" on the insides of the boots. They are NSN numbered differently on the inside of the boot sleeve as pictured, and for some reason the back of one the tongues is natural color. Both boots are the same maker and size. The size is 8 1/2 as noted in the photos.

The brown-cowhide roughout leather is EXCELLENT. The soles have never been treaded on anything. Mint new bootlaces. The soles are the typical black-corded rubberite of the period. 
Overall, a minty original set of USMC M51 roughout combat boots.
